      <hedline>
        <hl1>Weather Worries</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Jim Schwartz says Brian Fagan, in July 30 Op-Ed, suggests there might be no particular reason for extreme heat this summer; says it could also be result of pollutants dumped into atmosphere</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Brian Fagan (Op-Ed, July 30)  asks, ''Could it be that there is no particular reason for the extreme heat of this summer, except for slightly unusual positions of high pressure systems?''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Brian Fagan (Op-Ed, July 30)  asks, ''Could it be that there is no particular reason for the extreme heat of this summer, except for slightly unusual positions of high pressure systems?''</p>
        <p>This is a possibility. But could it also be that the thousands of tons of the pollutants we dump into our atmosphere every day are having drastic effects on our global system?</p>
        <p>Mr. Fagan's suggestion that we should not worry about global warming lulls us into a sense of security at a time when we should be worried about what we might be doing to our environment.</p>
        <p>If we follow his reasoning, we will never take any action to safeguard the earth until irreparable damage has been done.</p>
        <p>JIM SCHWARTZ  Chicago, July 30, 1999</p>
      </block>
